GCB vs non-GCB in DLBCL (15-000)
A comparison of clinical outcomes by genetic subtype in patients with newly diagnosed DLBCL
Most recent compile: 25 September 2019
Department of Biostatistics and Computational Biology
Dana Farber Cancer Institute
Contact:
Overall PI: Dr.Doctor, email
CRC: Contact Person, email
Statisticians:
Robert Redd, email
All analyses were performed using R version 3.6.0 (2019-04-26) and packages survival v2.44.1.1 for time-to-event analyses; and knitr v1.23 for reproducible research.

Design

Summarize the design of the study: one- or two-stage with sample size and statistical considerations.

Study objectives

The primary outcome was overall response rate (ORR).

The secondary outcomes were:

  • rate of PR, CR or better
  • progression-free survival
  • overall survival
  • safety

Statistical methods

All subjects will be evaluable for toxicity from the time of their first treatment with study drug.

Overall Survival (OS) will be measured from date of protocol therapy initiation until date of death and characterized using the Kaplan-Meier method.

Progression-free Survival (PFS) will be measured from date of protocol therapy initiation until date of documentation of progressive disease or death from any cause and calculated using the Kaplan-Meier method.

Time-to-event endpoints are estimated using the method of Kaplan and Meier with 95% confidence intervals calculated using Greenwoods method of variance estimation. Median follow-up is calculated using the reverse Kaplan-Meier method.

Responses to study treatment were reported as proportions with 95% exact binomial confidence intervals. Continuous measures summarized as median and range, and categorical variables are summarized as proportions.

Nominal variables were tested for association with continuous and other categorical variables using Wilcoxon rank-sum (or Kruskal-Wallis for three or more groups) or Fishers exact tests, respectively. Ordinal variables were tested using trend tests (Cuzick, KW, JT) where appropriate.

Statistical analyses were performed using R version 3.6.0 (2019-04-26).

Administrative Information

From April 2012 to May 2013, 50 patients were enrolled on study at BWH (n = 19, 38%), DFCI (n = 12, 24%), and MGH (n = 19, 38%). As per inclusion criteria, all patients were newly diagnosed diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL). Per protocol patients were analyzed by subtype, activated B cell-like (ABC) and germinal center B celllike (GCB).

50 patients received at least one dose of study treatment and were included in toxicity and response analyses.

Patient Characteristics

Patient characteristics are presented in Table 1. 29 (58% of) patients enrolled were male. The median age at diagnosis was 66 (range: 36 - 89). 40 (80% of) patients had International Prognostic Index (IPI) of two or more.

Treatment summary

Treatment toxicities

Toxicities attributed to study treatment (possible, probable, definite) are presented in Tables 3A and 3B. All patients received at least on dose of study treatment and were included in toxicity summary. The most common toxicities on study were Bone marrow hypocellular (n = 30, 60%), Hemolytic uremic syndrome (n = 29, 58%), Atrial fibrillation (n = 28, 56%), Anemia (n = 27, 54%), and Asystole (n = 27, 54%).

The highest grades experienced among all patients regardless of toxicity were 1 (n = 1/50, 2%), 2 (n = 4/50, 8%), 3 (n = 20/50, 40%), and 4 (n = 25/50, 50%).

Outcome summary

Response to treatment

The primary outcome was overall response rate (MR, PR, CR) at end of treatment. All patients received at least one dose of study treatment and were included in response assessment, and all patients were evaluated for EOT response.

The overall response rate of MR or better was 32/50, 64% (95% CI: 49 - 77%). 24 (48% of) patients experienced a PR or better at EOT (95% CI: 34 - 63%). 12 (24% of) patients experienced a CR or better (95% CI: 13 - 38%).

Time-to-event

Median follow-up was 20 months. Patients were followed for progression-free and overall survival; results are shown in Table 5.

The median OS and PFS were 24 (95% CI: 24 - NR) and 24 (95% CI: 21 - NR), respectively. 12- and 24-month PFS were 89 and 62 percent.

Median PFS by subtype was not reached and 24 months, p = 0.11.
